<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Broken Bow<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.40)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149'>Drew "Player27" Lichtenstein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 3, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> *NOTE: This article is pre-Mines of Moria, so none of those cards are take into account*<br />
<br />
Archery sucks. A lot. Well, OK, it&#8217;s the most powerful &#8220;thing&#8221; in the game for the fellowship side, but as a shadow player, you have to despise it. It&#8217;s your bane, its going to be the reason why your going to lose games more than anything else there is. The question is are you going to just roll over and watch your pumped up Cave Troll and his Keyward become nothing more than target practice or will you fight back?<br />
<br />
Most players know how archery work that&#8217;s its barely worth mentioning. You know the drill: Legolas and Aragorn with his Bow (normally pulled out with The Prancing Pony) exert themselves a bit to stop minions from ever even entering the skirmish phase. The other power member of this triad is Arwen: with her Bow and Splendor of Their Banners, she can exert twice to cause you another three wounds to worry about. Well that&#8217;s an extreme example, you could easily have five wounds (around three or four of which they distribute) on you before going into skirmishing. With the dreaded Ranger&#8217;s Versatility (which is guaranteed spots to play at sites seven and eight), getting minions to even fight can extremely difficult. The Tale of Gil-Galad and Sage of Enedil allow for even more directed wounds. Add in Double Shot which gives them free wounds and everything in their deck is either dedicated to making archery stronger or healing off members of the triad (duplicate copies, Aragorn, The Choice of Luthein, Athelas, etc&#8230;).<br />
<br />
It&#8217;s powerful, folks. It&#8217;s a beast. We&#8217;ve all had those games where we had enough twilight to drop our whole hand only to watch it go to waste. However, it doesn&#8217;t have to be this way. The nice thing about archery is if you can kill off one of the triad (particularly Aragorn or Legolas) you&#8217;re a large step close to victory.<br />
<br />
Taking it piece by piece, it&#8217;s important to strike them where they start: The Prancing Pony. The Prancing Pony is such a common start that it&#8217;s not even funny, with almost half of the decks out there using and abusing it. Green Dragon Inn has become my new hang out: bid five or six burdens with confidence and grab Sam early on. Of course, the ability to stop them from getting Aragorn isn&#8217;t that deadly: they could replace the site with Ulaire Neyla or, more likely, simply just draw another copy since they have multiples for healing. However, every little bit helps and if you can get a few minions (especially high vitality Nazguls that Legolas can&#8217;t gun alone) before Aragorn is out, it&#8217;s nice.<br />
<br />
However, it&#8217;s highly unlikely you&#8217;ll be able to slow them down enough before Aragorn and Bow comes out. Before going too in depth into strategy, here&#8217;s a small sampling of cards to keep in mind. Most of these cards have already been mentioned before, but it is important to keep them all in mind when trying to make effective anti-Archery strategies:<br />
<br />
-- Relentless Charge: For a while when I used any shadow deck I still threw in some Nazguls for their cheap roaming coasts and a pair of Relentless Charges. For the cost of one exertion, you can hit two (three if Arwen has her Bow) of the triad and save some of your other minions from death. It&#8217;s huge and worth considering for any deck that even just splashes in Nazguls.<br />
-- Hate: Basically, you choose who gets exerted instead of them. Useful if not just because instead of your Orc War Band or Morgul Hunter getting the wound your Ambusher or Assassin can.<br />
<br />
-- Bitter Hatred: Yes, this is powerful for all it requires is the ability to spot a Moria archer and an exhausted Arwen or Legolas is dead. Of course, any good archer player has to see this coming against Moria, whether they have it or not. They&#8217;ll either simply not exhaust Legolas or they&#8217;ll ping off the archer(s). However, the mere threat can be as powerful as actually using it.<br />
<br />
-- Uruk-Hai Armory, Goblin Archer, etc&#8230;: Basically any cards that subtract from the overall archery total aren&#8217;t too bad. Granted, their worst damage is going to be archery actions with Aragorn/Legolas and you can&#8217;t subtract from that, but the likes of Arwen and Double Shot can easily knock off another minion which direct archery didn&#8217;t get, and if you can get at least a couple guys past archery phase, you can get some damage in.<br />
<br />
-- Anduin Wilderlands: Worth mentioning, but almost all players with dedicated archery will use Pathfinders or Thor&#8217;s Map. Still use it, though, because if you catch them unprepared, you can turn their recently healed companions into exhausted ones before they even have the opportunity to heal. Of course, there&#8217;s a little Isengard card that has this same effect&#8230; (see below)<br />
<br />
As a whole, the above cards seem to have a recurring theme: hurt the archer. Unfortunately, all either occur before the actual archery phase (meaning they&#8217;ll have to be exhausted before then) or can be seen a mile away and prepared for (Bitter Hated). With constant ways to heal, the way to attack them has to be with minions: if they&#8217;re exhausted and facing guys, they&#8217;re bound to drop like flies eventually, right?<br />
<br />
It gets tough here since they&#8217;re able to pick and choose who to kill (and then Arwen can knock out any leftovers). High vitality minions who are cheap are absolutely essential here. If they&#8217;re forced to use most of their archery to shoot down a vitality four Morgul Hunter who would be strength of twelve in a skirmish, this will allow your cheaper Orcs to get into battle and go up against their companions and inflict more wounds by exerting. On this note, here&#8217;s a quick break down of each culture vs. archery:<br />
<br />
-- Uruk-Hai: Hurt the most since they really have no anti-archery cards. Also, its unlikely that you&#8217;ll be able to drop more than a few minions so once Lurtz is taken down, the others are much more easier to manage. However, their high vitality can be a savior, especially in the form of their Troops. Couple them up with another minions and your likely to get someone to survive into the skirmish phase. Also, don&#8217;t forget Orophin who can deal some damage from afar. Oh, wait, there is one major thing (intentionally skipped in the above card selection): Spies of Saruman. Is it useful? You bet. Drop this with a single Troop of Uruk-Hai and let the fun times roll. However, while it&#8217;s doubtful they&#8217;ll have Sleep, Caradhas with Gandalf, Albert Dreary is a distinct possibility. However, a dedicated Uruk-Hai deck needs four of these. Period. This and Snows is really their saving grace.<br />
<br />
-- Nazgul: High vitality helps a lot (and, of course, so does Relentless Charge), but one of the greatest strengths of a dedicated Nazgul deck is also one of their greatest weaknesses: The Ford of Brunien is a river, which means they can use A Ranger&#8217;s Versatility on that free or cheap Nazgul that you drop on them early on.  The Ford is suddenly a double edged sword: despite being able to get a free Nazgul, your almost guaranteed to lose two minions here. Is it worth the risk? As a whole, I&#8217;m almost tempted to say no. Yes, I recognize the sheer insanity of the power of the Ford, but the risk of your opponent causing your free minion to be dead at the cost nothing more than a Versatility that early on is damaging. However, other sites, Nazguls are useful in a mix with other minions. Drop a vitality four Nazgul to soak up archery and have another vitality three or four minion waiting in the wings. It could work with two Nazguls, however, their high cost against a deck that gives off little vitality can be detrimental.<br />
<br />
-- Sauron: One of the hardest cultures to play, Sauron also has one of the best chances against archery. Hate is powerful since it lets your cheap trackers take the wounds and let your Hunters and Wardens possibly go unscathed. Under The Watching Eye, if you can get them out, are also huge since they&#8217;ll eventually be forced to stack wounds on someone else beside Frodo. The way to work Sauron against them is to drop a few trackers in the early game, get out Watching Eye, and just rain down with minions from site six onwards. Hopefully Watching Eyes/Hate will cause enough of them to exert/wound to the point where Morgul Hunters and Wardens can break through and do damage. While they&#8217;ll heal, the rate of wounds should be enough to kill someone off. Unfortunately, archery will still do some major binging until then: they have access to Rumil from afar and if you ping an &#8220;exert-to-wound&#8221; Orc, they become that much less desirable. It&#8217;s basically a site nine kill for Sauron, but they have the highest chance (outside of Uruk-Hai with Spies).<br />
<br />
-- Moria: Swarm. Swarm. Swarm. The Cave Troll taking wounds here is good: if you can get enough guys out, having them force to exert out to kill him is very beneficial because it&#8217;ll let your other minions break through. While archery is most effective against Moria because one exertion can likely kill one minions, just keep dropping them with no fear. Moria Scouts come out for free and Runners are always adding twilight. Also, Goblin Armory is a MAJOR card here: it forces them to keep their exertion wound but your free from the attack. It&#8217;s a game breaker.<br />
<br />
Notice a major pattern here: conditions (Spies, Watching Eye, Armory) seem to hurt archery as much as any minion does. Expect to see some archery run Gandalf with Sleep (and, more likely) Albert Dreary. However, in all the match ups vs. archery you&#8217;ll notice one thing: they&#8217;re slow getting some of their cards out. Take advantage of this. Don&#8217;t see Gandalf or Dreary? Drop any Moria guy you have with decent strength (preferably a Scout) and an Armory and go to town. The more they stock their deck with anti-anti-archery cards, the less likely you are to see that killer Double Shot or first turn Aragorn&#8217;s Bow. It comes down to the same basic principle of every card game: know your match up.<br />
<br />
So, in conclusion, archery makes you play strategically instead of just throwing down minions for them to kill. However, it is beatable and once you get through their line of fire, your in the zone.<br />
<br />
Aim low, miss low,<br />
<br />
-Drew<br />
